WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:02.000
Hey everyone, welcome back!

00:02.000 --> 00:04.500
We're going to dip our toes into JavaScript,

00:04.500 --> 00:08.300
the magical programming language that makes web pages come alive.

00:08.300 --> 00:10.300
Ready to learn? Let's go!

00:11.300 --> 00:13.300
So why should you study JavaScript?

00:13.300 --> 00:14.500
Great question!

00:14.500 --> 00:19.000
JavaScript is one of the three languages every web developer should know.

00:19.000 --> 00:22.000
HTML, CSS, and JavaScript.

00:22.000 --> 00:24.000
Let's take a short look at each language.

00:25.000 --> 00:27.000
1. HTML

00:27.000 --> 00:30.500
To find content, think of this as the structure of your site.

00:30.500 --> 00:32.500
2. CSS

00:32.500 --> 00:35.500
Specifies the layout and style of your site.

00:35.500 --> 00:37.500
3. JavaScript

00:37.500 --> 00:41.500
It can change how websites behave, look, and interact with you.

00:41.500 --> 00:45.500
Think of it like the secret sauce that spices up your favorite meal.

00:45.500 --> 00:48.500
On this page, we use JavaScript for two things,

00:48.500 --> 00:51.500
changing to dark mode and that live clock.

00:51.500 --> 00:55.500
Here are some more simple examples showing the different ways JavaScript can work.

00:55.500 --> 00:59.500
First up, JavaScript can change HTML content.

00:59.500 --> 01:03.500
Imagine we want some text to change on our web page when a user clicks a button.

01:03.500 --> 01:07.500
We have a paragraph here with an ID called demo.

01:07.500 --> 01:11.500
JavaScript finds this paragraph and changes its HTML content to say,

01:11.500 --> 01:13.500
Hello JavaScript!

01:13.500 --> 01:15.500
See that?

01:15.500 --> 01:17.500
It's like magic.

01:17.500 --> 01:19.500
But cool.

01:19.500 --> 01:23.500
Next, we want an image to change at the click of a button.

01:23.500 --> 01:25.500
We have this image of a light bulb.

01:25.500 --> 01:30.500
To turn it on, we use a separate image of a lit light bulb and a little JavaScript magic.

01:30.500 --> 01:33.500
JavaScript can change HTML attribute values.

01:33.500 --> 01:39.500
And in this example, we just change the SRC or source attribute to turn the light on.

01:39.500 --> 01:41.500
Let's style things up.

01:41.500 --> 01:45.500
We can use JavaScript to change CSS styles too.

01:45.500 --> 01:47.500
Look at this example.

01:47.500 --> 01:49.500
Here we have three buttons.

01:49.500 --> 01:52.500
Using CSS and JavaScript, we can

01:52.500 --> 01:55.500
change font size, hide an element,

01:55.500 --> 01:57.500
or show an element,

01:57.500 --> 02:01.500
all triggered on user interaction making our page interactive and dynamic.

02:01.500 --> 02:06.500
JavaScript was created by Brendan Eich in 1995.

02:06.500 --> 02:10.500
It's totally different from Java and the official name is ECMA script.

02:10.500 --> 02:12.500
And here's a secret.

02:12.500 --> 02:14.500
You don't need to download JavaScript.

02:14.500 --> 02:16.500
It's already built into your browser.

02:16.500 --> 02:20.500
Yep, whether you're on a computer, tablet, or smartphone,

02:20.500 --> 02:22.500
JavaScript is ready to roll.

02:22.500 --> 02:24.500
And it's totally free.

02:24.500 --> 02:26.500
That's it for today's JavaScript intro.

02:26.500 --> 02:30.500
Now go play around with these examples and make your web pages come alive.

02:30.500 --> 02:31.500
See you next time.

02:31.500 --> 02:32.500
Thanks for watching.

02:32.500 --> 02:35.500
Like and subscribe to get notified about our latest videos.

02:35.500 --> 02:37.500
For more coding tips and tricks,

02:37.500 --> 02:41.500
keep it locked right here on w3schools.com.

02:42.500 --> 02:45.500
Don't forget to try out what you've learned in our interactive editor.

02:45.500 --> 02:47.500
Happy coding.

